   <abstract>The project described in this thesis will utilize a design-based research framework in order to design an online platform that will support the unique needs of Black, Indigenous, and Women of Color (BIPOC) Women in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) fields at historically Black colleges and universities (HBCU) and predominantly white institutions (PWI). Additionally, the project will also explore if the unique needs of BIPOC Women STEM faculty can be supported with an online tool. The project will be informed by a Black feminist framework, as the purpose of the platform is to support historically underrepresented communities in academia. Through the design process, I will shed light on the forms of oppression that constitute the creation of a platform in the first place. Utilizing a design-based research framework, a card sorting activity with community members will be used to inform features and goals of the platform. Proceeding findings from the card sorting activity, a prototype will be developed, then engaged with by community members. We will evaluate the overall success of the platform through surveys. What I am hoping to find with the implementation of this project is if an online space will support the unique funding needs of BIPOC Women faculty within the academic sphere.</abstract>
